Beffldes the term Ignorance or Error, the above-quoted definition of the Voluntary and Involuntary contains the term Force (Vis); we accordingly require a precise conception of Force. Force is of two kinds, Vis absoluta, and Vis compulsiva. Vis absoluta is physical force, superseding the Volition of the agent in the pro- duction of an effect3 as, for instance‘when a person forces another to sign a document by holding and guiding his hand3 and such force makes an act Involuntary. Vis compulsiva, Compulsion or intimidation (metus), e. g. inducing a man to sign by means of threats, leaves an action Voluntary. Of such cases Aristotle says: μικταὶ μὲν οὖν εἰσὶν αἱ τοιαῦται πράξεις, ἐοίκασι δὲ μᾶλλον ἑκουσίοις. Eth. Nic. 3, 1. ‘ Such acts have a mixed character, but if we are driven to decide we must pronounce them to be Voluntary.'
